Cost of Living Analysis

Soumya Pannala

Introduction

Reason for Interest: There are good and bad aspects to every country, ranging from safety to scenery. However, when considering moving to another country or operating a foreign business, money makes the first case. Evaluating what makes financial sense often precedes comparing the other factors that define a country. As such, a Cost of Living Analysis has real-world applications, allowing you to see the relationships between cost of living, average monthly income, and average individual tax rates across different countries and regions. Additionally, by creating a color-coded map and other visualizations, it will be easy to see which countries are most favorable in terms of finances. This analysis will serve as an informative resource for those engaging in foreign business planning or simply for individuals planning to relocate.

Importance: A countryâs cost of living determines how much income individuals need to cover basic expenses and it directly influences the amount of disposable income left over after essential spending. Countries vary widely in their cost of living due to differences in the price of basic necessities, such as housing, food, transportation, healthcare, education, and taxes. Understanding these variations is valuable for comparing economic conditions across countries, evaluating salary levels, identifying trends in affordability over time, and exploring how income, taxation, and savings interact to shape overall quality of life.

Questions of Interest

  1. What are the top ten financially favorable countries in terms of cost of living?
  2. What are the trends over the years in terms of lowering cost of living?
  3. How does cost of living differ across regions?
  4. Are countries with lower costs of living characterized by higher savings percentages and average monthly incomes?
  5. Are countries with lower costs of living also characterized by lower or higher tax rates? And are tax rates responsible for the variation in average monthly income and savings percentages unexplained by cost of living alone?
  6. What contributes greatest to a countryâs cost of living? Is it healthcare, education, transportation, or housing? Or are they all roughly equal?

About the Data

For this analysis, we will be using three separate datasets all found on Kaggle. The first is an extended Cost of Living Dataset for Countries while the second covers Cost of Living for Cities. Although the third dataset is solely focused on the year 2022, it has far more countries than the first dataset (Extended Cost of Living for Countries), adding useful information for a couple analyses when used in conjunction with the first two datasets.

The datasets have slight variations in the variables they use and their sizes so I have summarized each below:

  1. Regional Cost of Living Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/heidarmirhajisadati/regional-cost-of-living-analysis

    • Filename: Cost_of_Living_and_Income_Extended.csv

    • Size: 500 rows x 11 columns

    • Variable Descriptions:
      Country: The name of the country where the data was recorded.
      Region: The geographical region to which the country belongs (e.g., Asia, Europe).
      Year: The year when the data was recorded.
      Average_Monthly_Income: The average monthly income of individuals in USD.
      Cost_of_Living: The average monthly cost of living in USD, including essentials like housing, food, and utilities.
      Housing_Cost_Percentage: The percentage of income spent on housing expenses.
      Tax_Rate: The average tax rate applied to individualsâ income, expressed as a percentage.
      Savings_Percentage: The portion of income saved monthly, expressed as a percentage.
      Healthcare_Cost_Percentage: The percentage of income spent on healthcare services.
      Education_Cost_Percentage: The percentage of income allocated to educational expenses.
      Transportation_Cost_Percentage: The percentage of income spent on transportation costs.

  2. Cost of Living Index by Cities: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/debdutta/cost-of-living-index-by-country

    • Filename: Cost_of_living_index.csv

    • Size: 536 rows x 10 columns

    • Variable Descriptions:

      City: Includes city and country, and sometimes state if the country is the United States.
      Cost of Living Index (Excluding Rent): Cost of living indices are relative to New York City (NYC) which means that for New York City, each index should be 100. If another city has, for example, rent index of 120, it means that on an average in that city rents are 20% more expensive than in New York City. This is a relative indicator of consumer goods prices, including groceries, restaurants, transportation and utilities.
      Rent Index: is an estimation of prices of renting apartments in the city compared to New York City. If Rent index is 80, Numbeo estimates that price of rents in that city is on an average 20% less than the price in New York.
      Groceries Index: is an estimation of grocery prices in the city compared to New York City. To calculate this section, Numbeo uses weights of items in the âMarketsâ section for each city.
      Restaurants Index: is a comparison of prices of meals and drinks in restaurants and bars compared to NYC.
      Cost of Living Plus Rent Index: is an estimation of consumer goods prices including rent comparing to New York City.
      Local Purchasing Power: shows relative purchasing power in buying goods and services in a given city for the average wage in that city. If domestic purchasing power is 40, this means that the inhabitants of that city with the average salary can afford to buy on an average 60% less goods and services than New York City residents with an average salary.

  3. Cost of Living Index 2022: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ankanhore545/cost-of-living-index-2022

    • Filename: Cost_of_Living_Index_2022.csv

    • Size: 139 rows x 9 columns

    • Variable Descriptions: The variables in this dataset are mostly the same as those in the Cost of Living Index by Cities dataset. The variables include, country, cost_of_living_index, rent_index, cost_of_living plus rent, groceries_index, restaurant_price_index, and local_purchasing_power.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) & Visualization

Before we dive into the questions of interest, letâs start by creating a world map color-coded by cost_of_living so that we can start making and revising some initial predictions. Additionally, this map will give us an idea of what countries provide favorable cost conditions for various purposes, so that we can keep these ideal countries in mind as we continue through the analysis. This might lead us to understand which are truly ideal, as we want not only lower cost of living, but also favorable tax rates, savings percentages, average monthly incomes, and more. In other words, if a country has a low cost of living but a high tax rate, leaving us with less disposable income, impacting our ability to save as much as we would like, it would not truly be a financially favorable country.

First, we need to get world map data.

Code 
world_map <- map_data("world")

Now, we have to join our data with world map data.

Code 
chloropleth <- world_map %>% left_join(COL2022, by = c("region" = "country"))

As we look at this map, we must keep in mind that this is for the year 2022, since we are using the COL2022 dataset. This dataset simply covers more countries, so even though it is not 2025 data, it should be reasonably close to 2025 values for the majority of the countries as these things donât change too drastically unless there is a significant economic event, such as COVID back in 2019, which may have caused changes in cost_of_living for many countries.

With this map, we can understand at a glance that certain countries and regions have lower costs of living with the southern tip of Asia having the lowest costs of living. Other than China, the eastern part of Europe and Asia seem to have lower costs of living. South America and Mexico also have fairly low cost of living levels. If people plan to relocate or operate a foreign business, choosing these countries might be financially savvy, provided that tax rates in these entities, not to mention several other important factors, are also favorable.

Question 1: What are the top ten financially favorable countries in terms of cost of living?

Although we could use the countryCOL dataset, allowing us to compare cost_of_living and tax_rate side by side, the COL2022 dataset has many more countries giving us a better idea of which countries are favorable based on cost_of_living. With this information, if there is a certain country of interest to anyone planning to engage with the foreign country in any way, they could find current tax rates and see if it is still favorable for their income levels.

To still allow some comparison, I have created a second plot using the country_COL dataset showing the tax rates for available countries in 2022. This could at least help weed out some countries that are favorable by cost_of_living but unfavorable by tax_rate.

This must all be interpreted in context of your purposes, though. If you are planning to relocate, you want low cost_of_living and low tax_rate. However, with foreign business planning, sometimes having low cost_of_living but high tax_rate can help when trying to take deductions, and in some cases, you can always keep your business in that country, and, when applicable, shift income to a lower_tax jurisdiction in an armâs length transaction if you have multiple branches of your business in different countries.

Question 2: What are the trends over the years in terms of lowering cost of living?

First, letâs create a summary so that we only get one value for cost_of_living, average_monthly_income, and savings_percentage per country per year. I left in all the other variables so that we can reuse our summary for some of the later questions as well.

Code 
countryCOL_summary <- countryCOL %>%
  group_by(country, year) %>%
  summarise(cost_of_living = mean(cost_of_living, na.rm = TRUE),
    average_monthly_income = mean(average_monthly_income, na.rm = TRUE),
    savings_percentage = mean(savings_percentage, na.rm = TRUE),
    tax_rate,
    housing_cost_percentage,
    healthcare_cost_percentage, 
    education_cost_percentage,
    transportation_cost_percentage,
    region) %>%
  ungroup()

Before we create the plot, we should create a threshold level and use that to create a new variable that we can use to color-code points based on the relative levels of cost_of_living (high or low).

Code 
threshold <- median(countryCOL_summary$cost_of_living, na.rm = TRUE)

countryCOL_summary <- countryCOL_summary %>%
  mutate(level = ifelse(cost_of_living > threshold, "High", "Low"))

Now we can create a faceted plot by country so that we can see the trends for each country over the years from 2000 to 2025.

Code 
h <- ggplot(countryCOL_summary, aes(x = year, y = cost_of_living, color = level)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  facet_wrap(~ country, ncol = 1, scales = "free_y") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("High" = "red", "Low" = "lightseagreen")) +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0.25, 0.25))) +
  labs(title = "Cost of Living Trends by Country",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Cost of Living",
    color = "Cost of Living Level") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.border = element_rect(color = "black", fill = NA, linewidth = 1),
    strip.background = element_rect(fill = "grey95", color = "black"),
    strip.text = element_text(face = "bold"))
h
Code 
ggsave("Cost_of_Living_Trends.pdf")

We saw earlier that Brazil, Canada, and the United States all had favorable tax rates as of 2022. But when we look at their current cost_of_living values, only Brazil is favorable of the three countries. Besides Brazil, Germany, Mexico, India, and South Africa all have low cost_of_living values. Another pattern we can notice is that several countries experienced an increase in cost_of_living in 2019 or 2020 based on how soon the COVID pandemic reached that particular country. Notably, Australia, Brazil, France, Germany, and Russia saw decreases in cost_of_living around the time of the COVID pandemic.

Question 3: How does cost of living differ across regions?

We noticed earlier when looking at the map that some countries with lower cost_of_living levels were clustered together, but is there a regional pattern? To check, letâs create a series of boxplots that show us how the regions compare. Before we do this, weâll have to use the countrycode package we loaded in earlier. This package contains country and region variables. Since our COL2022 dataset has country but not region, we can use this package to add a new region variable using its specified mapping.

Code 
COL2022_summary <- COL2022 %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  summarise(cost_of_living = mean(cost_of_living_index, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
              mutate(region = countrycode(sourcevar = country,
                              origin = "country.name",
                              destination = "region"))

COL2022_summary$region <- as.factor(COL2022_summary$region)

Question 4: Are countries with lower costs of living characterized by higher savings percentages and average monthly incomes?

Code 
# List of countries
countries <- unique(countryCOL_summary$country)

# Loop to create stacked plots per country
for (c in countries) {
  
  country_data <- countryCOL_summary %>% filter(country == c)
  
  plot_col <- ggplot(country_data, aes(x = year, y = cost_of_living)) +
    #geom_line(color = "blue", size = 1) +
    geom_point(color = "darkblue", size = 2) +
    labs(title = "Cost of Living", x = "Year", y = "Cost of Living") +
    theme_minimal()
  
  plot_income <- ggplot(country_data, aes(x = year, y = average_monthly_income)) +
    #geom_line(color = "green", size = 1) +
    geom_point(color = "seagreen", size = 2) +
    labs(title = "Average Monthly Income", x = "Year", y = "Average Monthly Income") +
    theme_minimal()
  
  plot_savings <- ggplot(country_data, aes(x = year, y = savings_percentage)) +
    #geom_line(color = "red", size = 1) +
    geom_point(color = "darkred", size = 2) +
    labs(title = "Savings Percentage", x = "Year", y = "Savings Percentage") +
    theme_minimal()
  
  combined_plot <- plot_col / plot_income / plot_savings +
    plot_annotation(title = paste("Trends Over Time -", c))
  
  print(combined_plot)
}

While for some countries, there seems to be a pattern in the trends of these three variables, it is hard to tell and it doesnât seem to hold true for all the countries. More concrete analysis will help us determine if there truly is a pattern, which is what weâll do next.

Analysis

Question 4: Are countries with lower costs of living characterized by higher savings percentages and average monthly incomes?

While we were able to answer questions 1 through 3 with just EDA, question 4 needs a little more. We have gotten some information from our EDA on this question, but letâs see if we can take it a bit further with some analysis methods.

Code

Question 5: Are countries with lower costs of living also characterized by lower or higher tax rates? And are tax rates responsible for the variation in average monthly income and savings percentages unexplained by cost of living alone?

We saw earlier that some countries are favorable from a tax standpoint but not from a cost of living standpoint and vice versa. In contrast, there were a few other countries we identified that had somewhat favorable values for both. But, is there a general pattern? Letâs run a correlation to see. While weâre exploring how taxes play a role in all of this, letâs also see if tax rates influence average monthly income and savings percentages. Previously, we thought cost of living drove these metrics, but we found very weak correlations. Perhaps, tax rates play a bigger role in this part of the puzzle.

Code 
# Making sure there are no missing values in cost_of_living or tax_rate.
tax_data <- countryCOL_summary %>% 
  drop_na(cost_of_living, tax_rate)

# Checking if cost of living correlates to tax rates.
cor_COL_tax <- cor(tax_data$cost_of_living, tax_data$tax_rate, use = "complete.obs")

# Checking if tax rate correlates to savings percentage.
cor_tax_savings <- cor(countryCOL_summary$tax_rate, countryCOL_summary$savings_percentage, use = "complete.obs")

# Checking if tax rate correlates to average monthly income.
cor_tax_income <- cor(countryCOL_summary$tax_rate, countryCOL_summary$average_monthly_income, use = "complete.obs")

cor_COL_tax
[1] 0.05356275
Code 
cor_tax_savings
[1] -0.02292088
Code 
cor_tax_income
[1] 0.06404004

There is almost no relationship between these variable pairs. The first is just barely an extremely weak correlation showing that as cost_of_living increases, tax_rate goes up slightly. For the second, a slight negative correlation with an increase in tax_rate corresponding to a slight decrease in saving_percentage. The third is the strongest of the three, though still extremely weak, showing that as tax_rate increases, average_monthly_income increases a little. This follows the income effect of tax accounting which is when an individual workâs extra to make up for the money lost to taxes and make ends meet. In contrast, the substitution effect decreases an individualâs willingness to work as the larger tax burden discourages employees to put in more hours of work and instead take more time off from work for leisure.

While weâve already seen that there is hardly any correlation between tax rate and cost of living, letâs run a linear regression model just to confirm what correlation analysis suggested.

  labs(title = "Correlation Heatmap: Cost of Living, Income, Savings, Tax Rate",

Now, letâs also create a pie chart to capture these insights. Before we do so, we need to save these coefficient values in a data frame as well as their corresponding components. Next, we have to create a variable that stores the absolute value of the coefficients so that we can create the pie chart properly. The percent variable specifies the sizes of the different pieces of the pie while the label allows us to include not only the component name, but also the coefficient value in the legend.

Code 
coef_df <- data.frame(Component = c("Housing", "Transportation", "Healthcare", "Education"), Coefficient = c(-2.4745, 40.7934, -0.3246, -12.5958))

coef_df <- coef_df %>%
  mutate(Contribution = abs(Coefficient),
         Percent = Contribution / sum(Contribution) * 100,
         Label = paste0(Component, " (", round(Coefficient, 2), ")"))

Conclusion

Based on our analysis, cost of living is mainly influenced by transportation costs. While one would think that there would be a relationship between cost of living, tax rates, savings percentages, and average monthly income, many of our analyses showed weak correlations. However, there are some significant regional patterns, such as low cost of living in South Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa. Additionally, many countries that are favorable in terms of cost of living have been on a downward trend over the past few years, so if there is a particular country of interest to anyone, even if it doesnât currently have a favorable cost of living, in the coming years, it might attain reasonable levels if the country is currently on a downward trend. While many of our questions did not find very clear patterns or relationships between variables, another similar analysis on more comprehensive data might yield clearer answers.
